  abstract = {The goal of this study was to characterize the passive elastic behaviour of muscle and tendon tissues of rat tibialis anterior. For that purpose, tissue samples from 3 month old female Wistar rats (210{\textpm}11g) were mechanically tested in vitro. Moreover, an in vivo device was developed to measure the muscle--tendon unit response to increasing load. Mechanical tests, consisting of uniaxial loading along the longitudinal axis of tendon and muscle strips, revealed the nonlinear mechanical behaviour of these tissues. A material model was formulated and its parameters fit to the experimental data using the Levenberg--Marquardt optimization algorithm. The fit goodness was assessed and R2 values close to 1 and very low {$\varepsilon$} values were obtained. The passive behaviour of a future finite element model of a muscle--tendon unit will be validated against the in vivo passive extension tests by comparing the reaction force--extension curves.},
